{
  "texts": [
    "Note that this presentation is reminiscent of the graph representation explained above.",
    "When e 2 E, F(e) is a subset of X that is sometimes expressed with the more accurate notation (F, E)(e).",
    "It is referred to as the set of e-approximate elements of the universe of discourse, or alternatively, as the subset of the universe of discourse approximated by e.Henceforth SS E ðXÞ will represent the set of all soft sets on X.",
    "If E, the set of relevant characteristics of the elements of X, is common knowledge, we can drop the subindex and just use the notation SS(X).Two basic examples of soft sets are the full or absolute, and the null soft sets on X.",
    "The full soft set X is such that XðeÞ ¼ X for each e 2 E. In the interpretation by graphs, one has X ¼ E Â X."
  ]
}